Marques, your reviews' video quality keeps improving, and that is indeed something that always impresses me, however, please know and understand that not everyone is that crazy about cameras. This is something i've been noticing but you have a bias when it comes to cameras. if a phone is good for taking pictures, you would rate it highly whether it actually deserves such a rating or not.
I bought this phone (exynos version) and i am NOT happy with what i got. Performance you say is Good, which can't be farther than the truth here. Now to be fair, what i got was exynos version, and i use it for a lot of things like gaming, running benchmarks, testing software etc.

Re gaming, this phone just dies. Especially genshin impact, tower of fantasy. It is damn near unplayable and when it is playable, just not enjoyable due to lag and low fps. I tested the same games on older one plus phones, and the difference was night and day. older one plus phones outperformed this new phone every time. moreover the samsung software related to games is extremely bad. that is one of the reasons for these bad performances. genshin impact overclocks at 45fps. 30fps it says is smooth load wise, however, game experience is terrible.

Re battery, it is awful. i have to charge multiple times a day and have to watch my usage to make sure i don't run out of battery when outside. not reliable whatsoever. There are also some issues with software it seems where sometimes it would get stuck, heat up, and then attempt to restart, and doing so would drain massive percentages of battery. heating up is a problem as well in general. sometimes google maps drains massive amounts of battery, like 1% per minute even. very inconsistent.

Re Camera, it has been quite decent for the most part, however, it too drains battery very fast. if you do long sessions of photography, forget it, or keep a power source with you all times. Camera is quite inconsistent sometimes, which i suspect is owed to software updates. sometimes i would get great shots, and sometimes its just bad.

Design wise, i quite like it. it's a beautiful design. however, when it is heating up, due to metal rails, the whole phone gets heated and is uncomfortable to hold even.

I would suggest you do proper stress testing of the devices, and if it's not possible, please at least add a disclaimer that you have not tested it. I do realize that there are differences in SD and exynos however, the differences are not as big that all the above points i mentioned would be fixed by them (a friend used SD version as well).

Also, there are heating issues reported in devices with SD 888. All i can say is, please provide complete information. I really feel bad about this purchase, and it wasn't cheap.
everyday performance is silky smooth though, however, if i just want to scroll through news feed, i can do that with a $200 phone as well, why would i have to go the extra mile?! well, i'm gonna use this one until the phone expires, however, next phone i'm buying won't be samsung that's for sure.

After "upgrading" from my S9+ I instantly regretted it. Seriously how are these downgrades "not noticeable"?

First of all, the 1080p screen was obvious, I can see discolouration around texts where I couldn't see on the S9+ and things look pixelated. I used pop up window frequently (or at least used to) but at 1080p I can barely make out text unless I go full screen.

Secondly, SD card slot was a big deal breaker. I used to be able to transfer all my stuff in less than a second by slotting the SD card inside, now it takes an hour to transfer everything over.

Thirdly, the removal of the charger was a terrible move. They included a C to C cable which is incompatible with the charger that came with my S9+.

Lastly, the proximity sensor on this is horrendous. The screen doesn't turn on when I pull it away from my ear like my S9+ used to.

If Samsung keeps downgrading and removing features my next phone won't be a Samsung and that's for sure.

I always had LG phones. G3 ,G6 and the G8. As LG has gotten out of the phone market and it was nearly impossible to get a LG phone thru Sprint / T-mobile I decided to get a Nord. Well I tell you the Nord was Disappointing to say the least. It was a Oneplus Nord 10. It had all kinds of trouble and wasn't reliable at all. So I began to search for a phone that was reliable, fast and fun to use . I considered Samsung. I saw the S 21 series and thought it looked good and the only thing that made me hesitate was the price
I wasn't sure I wanted to spend that much again. But upon looking I found the S21 . The lowest price of the three S21 models. In fact it was so much better in price by about 300.00. So I read reviews and took a chance and ordered one. I have had it a day and a half and I absolutely love it. The only thing I wish was they had it in the color I had ordered which was red not Salmon or whatever the heck it is. And I do wish that it's a larger screen because of my vision but those are minor details and a bigger battery. It's fast , crisp pictures and has plenty of storage for my use. I absolutely recommend this phone. It is right up there and even better in many ways compared to my LG G8. Okay some fewer features but to be honest I find I really don't miss them all that much and the best part is it works right from the start without and rebooting or other complications that I had with the One plus Nord 10. Heck yeah , I love this phone. Worth every penny.

Battery: 3880mAh real capacity, not 4000mAh

With auto brightness and 120Hz, the phone is enough for a day, sometimes you have to recharge during the day, if you actively use the camera or play hard games + sit on the mobile Internet, then somewhere it is enough for 2-2.5 hours of screen work. Trust me, the S21 Plus is the GO-TO!!!. People say there's no difference...but there is!. I owned all 3 of the S21 models.
It feels much more premium and sturdy than the S21, but not as heavy, bulky, and awkward looking as the S21 Ultra. If you're worried about missing out on the 120hz QHD display on the Ultra, from the 120hz FHD on the S21 Plus....don't be. There is practically no noticeable difference, unless you are part of the 0.00000001% of the population who can see a pixel with the naked eye.
The S21 Plus retains the thinness of the S21, but having a wider, larger display makes it feel thinner, even making the camera bump feel very small. The S21 Plus feels significantly more premium than the S21, and it almost looks as if the screen quality is better than the S21. Not to mention the screen is completely flat, and stretched out to each corner, giving the phone a nice, slab/boxy feeling to it, but still feeling thin.
The S21 Ultra, is far too large, very heavy, very thick, and very awkward looking with the "very slightly" curved display, but rounded corners and thick sides....not to mention...the weight! It hurts your arms to hold.
there's a reason the S21+ has been the hardest to find in stock...and in my opinion it is definitely the best kept secret of the 3.

In recent years, Samsung phones have been disappointing. They don't offer significantly better values when compared to Apple anymore. The year over year improvements aren't significant yet the price keeps climbing. There was a time when Galaxy S mean premium or flagship. But Samsung follows Apple's footstep when they replace the iPhone XR with Iphone 11,  and now they make the S21 an expensive budget phone. It's 50% more expensive the S20FE, I'm not sure if it's 50% more value. Even budget phones from Chinese brands with half the price have FHD+ 120Hz display, and a Galaxy S21 has a FHD display??? Specs and performance asides, that's disrespecting customers. I'm using a Samsung Galaxy S7 Tablet, but I can't see myself buying a Samsung Galaxy S phone. The company that sells screen to other brands can't put the best screen on their supposedly flagship line up? What a joke! Perhaps people in the North America and EU will choose this since they are the only options available, money isn't a big problem, and Chinese phones aren't available. In more budget conscious markets, $750+ is flagship price, I don't see this phone fares well against Chinese competition like Xiaomi, Oppo, Oneplus. I understand Samsung likely removed MST since few people used it, but I think the reason few people used it was because few people knew about it. I think it was one of the few notable features that really made the Samsung Galaxy S series (and LG G series) stand out from other smartphones. I believe with some more advertising from Samsung about their MST feature, more people would have used it (and some may have even bought a Samsung over another phone for that feature.) With LG possibly leaving the smartphone market in a year or two (I really hope they don't), the number of devices with MST may become even more limited.

I'm against gimmicks for the sake of gimmicks, but it is unfortunate how phones are losing more and more features (headphones jacks, micro SD card slots, removable batteries, IR sensors, heart rate monitors ‚Äî all available on the S5, which had an MSRP of $650, and MST, which was available since the S6 (MSRP of $600 on some carriers, more on others)).

I can live without some of those features (don't need micro SD if plenty of storage available on the device, don't need removable battery if it's easy to disassemble the phone and replace it myself, I don't really need an IR sensor or heart rate monitor, though some people certainly may want the latter), but I do l really like having a headphone jack, and MST is a great feature to have.

Still, I'm glad they lowered the price in mostly good ways for this device (1080p is fine with me, plastic back is lighter and won't shatter, etc.), but still too expensive for me to consider it over something like a Pixel 4a: $350 vs $800, and that's the MSRP (not that I need a new phone now, but in case mine were to break). Getting a used or refurbished Pixel 4a would be even cheaper (plenty of those since it's been about half a year). If Samsung is charging $800, it better do a lot more than a $350 phone, and I'm just not seeing what features it's offering over it that I really care about (sure, it has 3 back cameras, but I rarely see anyone actually use anything but the main camera). Nonetheless, I'm glad they're experimenting with some of their other phones like the Galaxy Fold: it's out of my price range but that phone at least offers notable functionality not present on cheaper phones. The Z Flip is also neat (though I think the Moto Razr has better aesthetics, even if the hardware is better on the Flip.) Good to see Samsung is experimenting though.

You barely notice the plastic back? I'm surprised and disappointed, because it's the one thing you WILL notice right away!
After preordered the S21 for 760‚Ç¨ with 256GB and all the goodies, waiting 2 weeks, it's the first thing I noticed immediately and lost any excitement about the design, and the phone it self...
Everything else apart from the back sure is good, very good or ok, but the thing you feel everytime you hold the device in your hand, yes you notice!
The back felt cheaper than the A40, and of course, way cheaper than any glass or metal back, like the one on my Oneplus 5T.
I even think, making the back this kind of texturized and not smooth, makes it worse, because it was very slippery in my hands.
Dont get me wrong, plastic backs can feel good, like on my Sony Z3 Compact Tablet, or even of the cheap A40 (at least for me).
Also, I constantly had the feeling of being able to press it in, maybe because its such a slim and flexible back, looking at the teardowns...
If you would use a case, sure, you would not notice, but then, why have the better camera design in the first place?
As someone, who is using his phone without a case, just dont get the regular S21, and yes, even with ~250‚Ç¨ discount.

I'll be honest I prefer the look of the camera setup on the S21 compared to the S21 Ultra and I bought the S21 Ultra.

I'm not a camera nerd, I don't use any of the special camera features. All I wanted was the 1440p 120hz display and 512GB of storage, so I was forced to go with the S21 Ultra by default. If they had kept the expandable storage, I might have considered compromising on the screen, but I'm running out of storage and I've already got 366GB, so I didn't have any other option.

If Samsung had given us the S21+ with the 1440p 120hz display and kept the expandable storage, then that would have been the phone I bought. I also wouldn't have minded if they had used the same polycarbonate back that's on the S21, I put a polycarbonate backed case on my phone anyways and I like the feel and durability it provides.

The insane thing is that they could have done both of these things extremely easily, it's not even a stretch. Even if finding space in the phone to keep the expandable storage was an issue, I would be fine with downsizing the battery to 4500mAh in order to make the space.

I have no doubt that I'll love my Phantom Navy S21 Ultra, but they really missed an opportunity here to make the perfect phone.

Glad he talked about how the screen looks fine. So many people with a fundamental lack of understanding around how digital displays work are out talking shit. An FHD display is totally fine at this screen size. Especially when there are other elements bolstering the overall image quality. I have a S21+ and the screen easily looks superior to my S10+ display despite the lower resolutions. That's due to refinements made to the panels. This display is brighter, shows color more accurately, and displays less off axis color shift. AND it actually looks a bit sharper than my work issued N20 Ultra. This is likely due to that display being QHD but rendering internally at FHD to maintain 120fps. An upscaled image will ALWAYS look worse than a native image. Samsung, I think, was wise to implement these FHD displays. Because in addition to all of that, driving fewer physical pixels also means better battery life.

This would not work for anybody trying to monitor their Diabetic blood sugars because the new devices rely on NFC to transfer data securely and unlimited. That means people will have to carry around the manufacturer monitor than just scanning with your phone. Most people have their phones with them all the time so they didn't have to worry if insurance would cover it. Now if you upgrade without NFC, you will have to consider this and if it will become inconvenient for you all over again. Being able to scan as much as you want as long as you have your phone charged is a life saver for all Diabetic people trying to manage the sugars better without having to stick your finger several times a day. Plus you don't have to write down your numbers for your endocrinologist because it transmits it to them automatically which allows them to adjust your insulin correctly. Samsung hit a home run with the S21! They made a very PRACTICAL flagship phone by eliminating the expensive features on the S20 that most people either don't use or don't care about and LOWERED the price from $1000 (S20) down to $800 (S21).

Plastic back - Compared to glass, it's more durable, lighter and costs less to produce and replace if damaged. I love it!

SD card - Samsung keeps it simple. With just a $50 upgrade to the 256GB storage option and the cheap access to cloud storage these days, there's really no need to clutter up new phones with SD card hardware. This lowers the price and complexity of the phone and makes it a bit lighter too.

Screen resolution - On a 6.2 inch screen 1080p works great! It's a waste of money to go with any higher resolution. The human eye can't really tell the difference.

Flat screen - A superior choice! Curved screens may look good to some but they're problematic with unwanted touch inputs at the edges. They are also expensive to produce and replace.

MST - Samsung Pay no longer has MST (Magnetic Secure Transmission) on the S21 series but that's OK! Almost every payment system now has NFC so there's no longer a need to build expensive tech into newer phones that is NOT needed. MST is history.
